SIMPLE: shout
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shout
<hw>Shout</hw> <pr>(shout)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Shouted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shouting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>shouten</ets>, of
unknown origin; perhaps akin to <ets>shoot</ets>; cf. Icel.
<ets>sk⟦umac⟧ta</ets>, <ets>sk⟦umac⟧ti</ets>, a taunt.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter a sudden and loud outcry, as in joy, triumph,
or exultation, or to attract attention, to animate soldiers,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Shouting</qex> of the men and women eke.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>shouted</qex> thrice: what was the last cry for?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To entertain with refreshments or the like
gratuitously; to treat.</def> <mark>[Slang, Australia & U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To shout at</b></col>, <cd>to utter shouts at; to deride
or revile with shouts.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shout
<hw>Shout</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter with a shout;
to cry; -- sometimes with <xex>out</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>shout</ex>, or
to <ex>shout</ex> out, a man's name</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To treat with shouts or clamor.</def> <rj><au>Bp.
Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To treat (one) to something; also, to give
(something) by way of treating.</def> <mark>[Slang, Australia & U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shout
<hw>Shout</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A loud burst of voice or
voices; a vehement and sudden outcry, especially of a multitudes
expressing joy, triumph, exultation, or animated courage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Rhodians, seeing the enemy turn their backs, gave a great
<qex>shout</qex> in derision.</q> <rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A gratuitous entertainment, with refreshments or the
like; a treat.</def> <mark>[Slang, Australia & U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shouter</ent>⟦br⟧
